1. Executive Summary
SunSafe is an Android-based health application designed to address the growing global concern of overexposure to ultraviolet (UV) radiation. Skin cancer rates have risen dramatically worldwide, with the World Health Organization reporting that 1 in 3 cancers diagnosed is skin cancer. Most cases are preventable through proper sun protection habits.

SunSafe leverages built-in smartphone sensors—specifically the ambient light sensor and GPS—combined with external weather APIs to provide users with personalized, real-time UV exposure tracking. The app calculates safe sun exposure times based on skin type, location, and current UV index, then alerts users when they approach their limit.

Unlike existing weather apps that only display a UV number, SunSafe provides actionable, personalized recommendations and maintains a historical record of sun exposure for long-term health monitoring.

2. Problem Statement
The Current Situation
Lack of Awareness: Most people check weather forecasts for temperature and rain but ignore UV index data.

Generic Advice: Existing apps provide a UV number but don't translate it into personalized safe exposure times.

Forgetfulness: People intend to apply sunscreen but forget, especially during prolonged outdoor activities.

Health Consequences: Overexposure leads to sunburn, premature aging, and increased skin cancer risk.

Vitamin D Dilemma: People either avoid sun completely (risking deficiency) or overexpose (risking skin damage).

The Gap
There is no simple, automated tool that:

Tracks how long you've actually been in the sun.

Compares it against your personal safe limit.

Reminds you to reapply sunscreen.

Helps you balance sun protection with vitamin D needs.

SunSafe fills this gap using sensors already in your pocket.

3. Project Objectives
Primary Objectives
Automate Sun Exposure Tracking: Use the ambient light sensor to detect when the user is in direct sunlight and for how long.

Personalize Safe Limits: Calculate individualized safe exposure times based on skin type (Fitzpatrick scale), UV index, and sunscreen use.

Provide Proactive Alerts: Notify users before they reach their limit and remind them to reapply sunscreen.

Educate Users: Display UV index in an understandable format (Low, Moderate, High, Very High, Extreme).

Secondary Objectives
Vitamin D Optimization: Suggest optimal sun time for vitamin D synthesis based on skin type and location.

Historical Tracking: Maintain exposure history for health trend analysis.

Report Generation: Export PDF summaries for dermatologist consultations.

Community Heatmap: (Optional) Show UV intensity across different locations anonymously.

